# {{PROJECT_NAME}} — Agent Context

This project is built by autonomous Claude Code sessions directed by the orchestrator. Read this
before any task.

## Always on
- Follow `karpathy-guidelines` at all times: simplest change that meets the acceptance criteria,
  surgical edits, surface assumptions, define verifiable success criteria.

## Memory layer (REQUIRED)
- Durable knowledge lives in `docs/` as markdown. Once per ticket, append a short, cited entry
  (what changed, why, ticket id, PR link). The commit hook blocks a commit with no `docs/` file
  staged, so include the entry with your work — don't pad it onto every WIP commit.

## Context hydration (every session — be economical)
Each session is fresh and stateless, so reconstruct context before acting — but read the minimum that
makes you correct. Start from the **latest** comment plus anything **since your last state move**, and
the ticket's acceptance criteria. Pull in the GitHub PR thread, the repo `docs/` memory, and
git history only when you actually need them (e.g. read the PR thread on a rework). The comment trail is
the source of truth for *what to do next*; the rest is for *how*. Don't re-read the whole history when
the latest comment already tells you what to do.

## Safety (you run with permissions bypassed)
These prompts are the only guardrail: never commit or exfiltrate secrets; never weaken, skip, or delete
tests or edit CI/hooks to go green (fix the code); never force-push or commit to the base branch; stay
within this repo and the ticket's scope.

## Commands
- Lint: `npm run lint`
- Build: `npm run build`
- Test: `npm test`
(Adjust per project language; the commit hook reads `LINT_CMD`/`BUILD_CMD`/`TEST_CMD`.)

## Workflow
Your specific role (builder / reviewer / QA) and its steps are provided in the session's system
prompt. Honor the board state machine and the `🤖 [role] FROM → TO` comment convention.
